---
Background:  

Consider an open quantum system described by a single harmonic oscillator of frequency $\Omega$ and unit mass, coupled bilinearly to an environment of $\mathcal{N}$ independent harmonic oscillators. The Hamiltonian is
\begin{align*}
    H_{\rm s,0} &= \frac{P^2}{2} + \frac{\Omega^2}{2} Q^2,\\
    H_{\rm E,0} &= \sum_{j=1}^\mathcal{N} \left( \frac{p_j^2}{2} + \frac{\omega_j^2}{2} q_j^2 \right),\\
    H_{\rm int}(t) &= - c(t) Q \sum_{j=1}^\mathcal{N} q_j,
\end{align*}
where $c(t) = c\,\chi(t)$, with $c>0$ and $\chi(t)$ a general switching function, and all operators are in the Heisenberg picture. The system interacts with the environment starting at $t=0$. The Heisenberg equations of motion produce the quantum Langevin equation for $Q(t)$:
\begin{align*}
\ddot{Q}(t) + \Omega^2 Q(t) + \int_0^t\!\!{\rm d}t'\,\Sigma(t,t') Q(t') = \zeta(t),
\end{align*}
where the dissipation kernel is
\begin{align*}
\Sigma(t,t') &= -\chi(t)\chi(t')\Gamma(t-t'),\qquad \Gamma(t) = \sum_{j=1}^{\mathcal{N}} \frac{c^2}{\omega_j} \sin(\omega_j t),
\end{align*}
and $\zeta(t) = \chi(t) \xi(t)$ with $\xi(t) = c \sum_{j=1}^\mathcal{N} q^{(\mathrm{h})}_j(t)$ for homogeneous solutions $q^{(\mathrm{h})}_j$.

Let the switching function be a sum of $N$ Dirac deltas of fixed support $[0,T]$,
\begin{align*}
\chi(t)=\frac{T}{N} \sum_{k=1}^N \chi(t_k)\delta(t-t_k), \qquad t_k = \frac{kT}{N}.
\end{align*}
Assume that $Q(0)$ and $P(0)$ are the system's initial position and momentum operators, and $\zeta(t_k)$ are given functions or operators corresponding to the noise at sample times.

Define $K_{t,t_l}$ for $t\geq t_l$ as
\begin{align*}
K_{t,t_l} = \frac{T^2}{N^2} \sum_{k=1}^N \Sigma(t_k, t_l) \Theta(t_k - t_l) \frac{\sin[\Omega(t-t_k)]}{\Omega} \Theta(t-t_k).
\end{align*}
Let $\bm Q = [Q(t_1), ..., Q(t_N)]^\top$ and define the $N\times N$ strictly lower triangular matrix $\mathbf{K}$ with entries
\begin{align*}
K_{li} = \frac{T^2}{N^2}\sum_{k=1}^N \Sigma(t_k, t_i) \Theta(t_k - t_i)\frac{\sin[\Omega(t_l - t_k)]}{\Omega}\Theta(t_l - t_k)
\end{align*}
and define $\mathsf{K} = \sum_{n=0}^{N-1} \mathbf{K}^n$.

For arbitrary $t>0$, define the functionals
\begin{align*}
G[f](t) = f(t) + \sum_{l,i=1}^N K_{t,t_l}\,\mathsf{K}_{li} f(t_i)
\end{align*}
where for the system functions, $f_Q(t) = \cos(\Omega t)$, $f_P(t) = \sin(\Omega t)/\Omega$, $f_\zeta^{(k)}(t) = \sin[\Omega(t-t_k)] \Theta(t-t_k)/\Omega$.

Task:

Using the definitions, assumptions, and constructions above, derive an explicit expression for the solution $Q(t)$ as a linear combination of $Q(0)$, $P(0)$, and the set $\{\zeta(t_k)\}$, in terms of the functionals $G[f]$ for $f_Q$, $f_P$, and $f_\zeta^{(k)}$.

